    rationale: "The continuity equation states that in a closed, incompressible fluid system, volumetric flow rate (Q) is conserved: Q = A\u2081v\u2081 = A\u2082v\u2082. Therefore: v\u2082 = A\u2081v\u2081/A\u2082 = (4 cm\u00b2 \u00d7 10 cm/s) / 1 cm\u00b2 = 40 cm/s. When the tube narrows (area decreases), velocity must increase proportionally to maintain the same flow rate. This is why blood velocity is highest in the aorta (small cross-sectional area) and slowest in the capillaries (enormous total cross-sectional area). Velocity does not decrease in a narrowed tube \u2014 that would violate conservation of mass. Velocity is not constant throughout \u2014 it varies inversely with area. The 160 cm/s answer confuses the continuity equation with Bernoulli's Principle.",
